Introduction

In the previous article we have looked at average risks and returns of S&P 500 and other foreign stocks. Have you ever thought how often the rare events can happen? For example, how often and with which probability the returns can exceed a particular level?

In this article, I will introduce some key mathematical concepts and examples of code on Python to answer these curious questions using the example of S&P 500.

Data used

As in the previous blog post I'm going to use Yahoo Finance API to get daily data of S&P 500 historical prices.

import yfinance as yf
import pandas as pd

pd.options.mode.chained_assignment = None
data = yf.download( 
        # tickers list or string as well
        tickers = "^GSPC",

        # use "period" instead of start/end

        # fetch data by interval (including intraday if period < 60 days)

        # (optional, default is '1d')
        interval = "1d",

close_data = data.iloc[:, data.columns.get_level_values(0)=='Close']

Where are extreme returns, Lebowski?

S&P 500 daily returns

close_data['returns'] = close_data['Close'].pct_change()

As we see, the daily returns of S&P 500 have some kind of normal distribution, with tails. The tails are the most curious part of the distribution that is formed by the biggest (maximums) and smallest (minimums) S&P 500 returns. Let's look at them.

S&P 500 maximum daily returns

For that, I will take monthly minimums and maximums.


close_data['year'] = close_data.index.year.to_list()
close_data['month'] = close_data.index.month.to_list()
maximums = pd.DataFrame(close_data.groupby(['year', 'month']).max()['returns'])
minimums = pd.DataFrame(close_data.groupby(['year', 'month']).min()['returns'])
maximums.median(), maximums.mean(), maximums.max()
(returns 0.014499
dtype: float64,
returns 0.016958
dtype: float64,
returns 0.1158
dtype: float64)

As we see, the maximums have a kind of right heavy tailed distribution meaning that the more daily return the less frequent it is - sounds logical :)

The median and mean of maximum daily returns are ~ 1.5%. The maximum all-time daily return is ~11.5%.

S&P 500 minimum daily returns

Similarly for minimums, but reversed:

minimums.median(), minimums.mean(), minimums.min()
(returns -0.013725
dtype: float64,
returns -0.016523
dtype: float64,
returns -0.204669
dtype: float64)

The median and mean of minimum daily returns are also ~ -1.5%. The minimum all-time daily return of the S&P 500 is about -20%. It reminds us again about the potential risk of stock market, so be careful.

3 distributions, 3 friends of extreme value theory

The mathematicians (Leonard Henry Caleb Tippett, Jenkinson and Mises) have shown that the series of maximums / minimums converge to particular functions. I will skip mathematical foundation from the textbook, but will show these 3 exponential functions:

  • G(x)=eexG(x)=eex - Gumbel Distribution
  • G(x)=e(x)G(x)=e(x) - Frechet Distribution
  • G(x)=e[x]G(x)=e[x] - Weibull Distribution

Generalization

These 3 distributions were combined into a single distribution and called the generalized extreme value distribution (GEV):

  • G(x)=e[1+(x)]1/+G(x)=e[1+(x)]+1/ where is the location parameter, >0>0 is the scale parameter, is the shape parameter.

When 00, GEV tends to a Gumbel distribution.

When >0>0, GEV tends to the Frechet distribution. Replace =1=1 and see for yourself what you get.

When <0<0, GEV tends to the Weibull distribution. Replace =1=1 and check.

It's quite convenient to use 1 distribution instead of 3 and as a result only 1 function in statistical packages. It reminds me of the Power Rangers series, when the heroes teamed up to turn into one powerful robot to defeat evil :)

Modeling and validation

I will use scipy package to estimate GEV parameters of the historical S&P 500 maximums.

from scipy.stats import genextreme
shape, loc, scale = genextreme.fit(maximums.values)
shape, loc, scale
(-0.20156688985805715, 0.012296443364258943, 0.005644137398833107)

We have got estimates for parameters of GEV distribution:

  • the shape parameter is ~ -0.2
  • the location parameter is ~ 0.01
  • scale is ~ 0.006

It looks like S&P 500 daily returns tend to the Weibull distribution since shape parameter is less than 0.

Let's look if our sample is different from the random sample generated from this distribution and get a sense of goodness of fit.

import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import numpy as np

l = loc + scale / shape

xx = np.linspace(l, l+0.14, num=1000)
yy = genextreme.pdf(xx, shape, loc, scale)

hist, bins = np.histogram(maximums.values, bins=12, range=(0, 0.12), density=True)
plt.bar(bins[:-1], hist, width = 0.009, align='edge')

plt.plot(xx, yy, '-r', alpha=0.5, linewidth=5)
plt.show()

Looks good! It repeats well the distribution of daily returns, especially that it has a heavy right tail.

Answering the questions

Now is the most interesting part for traders and market practitioners. Knowing all of this helps us to answer the following practical questions:

  • what is the probability that the maximum daily return Z of S&P 500 will be less than or equal x = 2% next month?
  • what is the probability that the maximum daily return Z of S&P 500 will be greater than 4% next month?
  • what is the probability that the maximum daily return Z of S&P 500 will be between 2% and 4% percents next month?

We can calculate this from the cumulative distribution function (CDF) of the GEV distribution.

G(x)=P(Zx)=e[1+(x)]1/+G(x)=P(Zx)=e[1+(x)]+1/

Of course we can take pen and paper, take shape, loc, scale estimated parameters and put them instead of ,,,, in the equation. But let's continue using scipy and python :) and answer each of the questions step by step:

genextreme.cdf(0.02, shape, loc, scale)
0.7412089965778758
1 - genextreme.cdf(0.04, shape, loc, scale)
0.032426358612746786
genextreme.cdf(0.04, shape, loc, scale) - genextreme.cdf(0.02, shape, loc, scale)
0.22636464480937746

So the answers are:

  • what is the probability that the maximum daily return Z of S&P 500 will be less than or equal x = 2% next month? - the probability is ~ 74%
  • what is the probability that the maximum daily return Z of S&P 500 will be greater than 4% next month? - the probability is ~ 3%
  • what is the probability that the maximum daily return Z of S&P 500 will be between 2% and 4% percents next month? - ~23%

Another interesting question we might be interested in is how frequently the S&P daily return is greater than 4%?

We know that the probability of this event is 3% per month. Then the period is Time=1/P(A)=1/0.0333Time=1/P(A)=1/0.0333 months. So we can expect that the daily return is greater than 4% every 33 months or almost 3 years on average.

The simple interpretation behind is in the following: we expect that the event occurs next month with a particular probability or months after until the probability reaches 1. So we are interested in how many months should pass before it happens.

Conclusions and further thoughts

In this article we have investigated and modelled the extreme values that are far enough from average values. The results once again reminded us about risks of stock markets: for example, the minimum all-time daily return of the S&P 500 is about -20% that can cause a great loss to the portfolio of the investor.

At the same time, we have modelled these extreme returns with GEV distribution, reduced the uncertainty and opened the opportunity for trading strategies based on this theory.

On the other hand, there are some questions come to my mind:

  • we have taken data for ~70 years of S&P 500 historical data. The structure of S&P 500 could change for this period as well as economics of US, World. Thus, extreme returns could also change and, as a result, GEV distribution based on them might have other parameters.
  • how confident are we that S&P 500 maximum returns tend to Weibull distribution and not other? In other words, how our parameters are significantly different from zero?

All of these definitely require more deep analysis.
